(485, 169, 'ccf_submission_data', 'a:3:{s:12:"contact-name";a:2:{s:5:"first";s:5:"david";s:4:"last";s:8:"dennison";}s:13:"contact-email";s:17:"dayv513@yahoo.com";s:16:"contact-question";s:1953:"August 2, 2015 Proposed Charitable Venture to Assist Handicapped and /or Cancer Treatment Patients in the Tri-County Area to Achieve a Better Quality of Care in Their Treatment and Recovery Over the past several years, I have been unable to walk, and this has been to a great degree undiagnosed as to why. I was unable to obtain assistance due to the fact that funding simply wasn’t available in this area. I was finally diagnosed with stage 4 small cell lung cancer that has metastasized into my brain, and I must travel from Trenton to Gainesville on a daily basis to be treated with radiation and chemotherapy. Because of Medicaid, the transportation available would take me approximately 8 hours or more per day, and I would be mixed with numerous people that would tear down my immunities which would almost certainly bring about my death. Funding simply isn’t there to assist people in such dire straits. I contacted Carrie A. Mizell, the editor to the Gilchrist County Journal, and I was given support of an idea that I had. We may not have funding, but we have good hearted people. We have a loving community. Why not reach out to automobile dealerships, local businesses, churches, or just some good old fashioned good hearted people that would be willing to loan the use of a van, truck, or suv with an electric lift or ramp on it, possibly equip it with a mobility scooter or electric wheelchair. Put a cancer ribbon on the vehicle, put your name on it as a sponsor, and help save lives in your community. The Journal will give free publicity, and the television and radio will certainly follow suit, and for a small investment, which you retain because this is simply a loan or use of your asset, you get miles and miles of positive public relations. My name is David Dennison, and I propose this project for the good of the community. Help us to save our lives. I can be contacted at 352-210-2099. Respectfully Submitted, David Dennison";}'),
